<DOC><DOCNO> AP890921-0094 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1227EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Hugo-GuadeloupeCrash 2ndLd-Writethru   09-21 0222</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Hugo-Guadeloupe Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0555,0225</SECOND><HEAD>Rescue Helicopter Crashes Into Sea; 6 Dead, 8 Missing</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with six dead, report of loud noises fromhelicopter during takeoff. No pickup.</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A French air force helicopter aiding in rescueefforts near the hurricane-stricken island of Guadeloupe crashedinto the sea, and officials said five bodies were recovered today.   The body of a sixth man, who was being evacuated from theoutlying island of Desirade, was recovered shortly after thehelicopter went down Wednesday night, said officials from theGuadeloupe capital, Point-a-Pitre. Three other people remainedmissing.   Chances were fading that searchers in helicopters and fishingboats would find them alive, the officials said.   The twin-engine Puma plunged into the Caribbean about a half-milesoutheast of the outlying island of Desirade while evacuatingBernard Berchel, who had suffered head injuries when Hurricane Hugohit on Sunday, officials said.   Also on the helicopter were Berchel's son, four medical workersand the helicopter's crew of three, the officials said.   The cause of the accident was unknown, but witnesses todayreported hearing unusually loud mechancial noises as the helicopterlifted off from Desirade, about six miles east of Guadeloupe.   The helicopter was part of ongoing rescue efforts involving about3,000 French servicemen assisting civil authorities cope with theaftermath of Hugo.</TEXT></DOC>